\f0\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanita}}. Widely distributed across {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Europe}}, but now sprouting in other parts of the world, 
\f0\i A.\'a0phalloides
\f1\i0  forms {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mycorrhiza#Ectomycorrhiza"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 ectomycorrhizas}} with various broadleaved trees. In some cases, the death cap has been introduced to new regions with the cultivation of non-native species of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oak"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 oak}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chestnut"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 chestnut}}, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinus"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 pine}}. The large fruiting bodies ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mushroom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 mushrooms}}) appear in summer and autumn; the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pileus_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 caps}} are generally greenish in colour with a white {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stipe_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 stipe}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamella_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 gills}}. Cap colour is variable, including white forms (see Taxonomy below), and thus not a reliable identifier. \
These toxic mushrooms resemble several edible species (most notably {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caesar%27s_mushroom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Caesar's mushroom}} and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volvariella_volvacea"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 straw mushroom}}) commonly consumed by humans, increasing the risk of accidental {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poison"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 poisoning}}. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amatoxin"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amatoxins}}, the class of toxins found in these mushrooms, are {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thermostability"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 thermostable}}: they resist changes due to heat, so their toxic effects are not reduced by cooking. \

\f0\i A.\'a0phalloides
\f1\i0  is one of the most poisonous of all known mushrooms. It is estimated that as little as half a mushroom contains enough toxin to kill an adult human. It has been involved in the majority of human deaths from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mushroom_poisoning"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 mushroom poisoning}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_phalloides#cite_note-benjamin200-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [1]}} possibly including the deaths of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Emperor"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Roman Emperor}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudius"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Claudius}} in AD 54 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holy_Roman_Emperor"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Holy Roman Emperor}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_VI,_Holy_Roman_Emperor"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Charles VI}} in 1740. It has been the subject of much research, and many of its biologically active agents have been isolated. The principal toxic constituent is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha-amanitin"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 \uc0\u945 -amanitin}}, which damages the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liver"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 liver}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kidneys"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 kidneys}}, causing {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liver_failure"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 liver}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kidney_failure"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 kidney failure}} that can be fatal. \
